    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Light emission that follows the absorption of energy by a substance from sources such as visible light, infrared light, ultraviolet light, electricity, cathode rays or x-rays, and that continues for a relatively long time after the energy supply has ceased.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000076943/Academic Press Dictionary of Science and Technology (1992)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Una emisión de luz que sigue a la absorción de energía por una substancia de fuentes como luz visible, infrarroja, electricidades, ultravioleta, electricidad, rayos del cátodo o rayos X y que continúa durante un tiempo relativamente largo después que el suministro de energía ha cesado.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Lichtemissie die het gevolg is van energieabsorptie door een stof uit bronnen zoals zichtbaar licht, infrarood licht, ultraviolet licht, elektriciteit, kathodestraling of röntgenstraling, en die vrij lang na het stopzetten van de energievoorziening aanhoudt.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052381/Van Dale Engels-Nederlands (1989)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>物質吸收可見光、紅外光、紫外光、電流、陰極射線或X射線等來源的能量，因而出現光的放射，這個光源在能量供應終止後仍持續一段相當長的時間。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
